NAME
    printf - format and print data

SYNOPSIS
    printf FORMAT [ARGUMENT]...

DESCRIPTION
    Print ARGUMENT(s) according to FORMAT, to standard output.

    FORMAT is a string that may contain plain text, C-style escape
    sequences, and format specifications (beginning with '%'). If there
    are more ARGUMENTs than FORMAT directives, FORMAT is reused until
    all ARGUMENTs are consumed.

ESCAPE SEQUENCES
    \\      Literal backslash
    \a      Alert (BEL)
    \b      Backspace
    \c      Produce no further output
    \e      Escape
    \f      Form feed
    \n      Newline
    \r      Carriage return
    \t      Horizontal tab
    \v      Vertical tab
    \NNN    Character with octal value NNN
    \xHH    Character with hexadecimal value HH
    \uHHHH  Unicode character (UTF-8 encoded)

FORMAT DIRECTIVES
    %%      A literal '%'
    %d, %i  Decimal integer
    %u      Unsigned decimal integer
    %o      Unsigned octal
    %x, %X  Unsigned hexadecimal (lower/upper case)
    %e, %E  Floating point in scientific notation
    %f      Floating point in fixed notation
    %g, %G  Shortest of %e or %f
    %s      String
    %c      Single character (first character of argument)
    %b      String, interpreting backslash escapes (like echo -e)
    %q      String quoted for safe reuse as shell input

    Width and precision modifiers are supported between '%' and the
    conversion character: %-10s (left-align in 10-char field),
    %08d (zero-pad to width 8), %.5f (5 decimal places).

OPTIONS
    --version
        Output version information and exit.

    --help
        Display help and exit.

EXAMPLES
    printf "Hello, %s!\n" "World"
        Print a formatted greeting.

    printf "%d + %d = %d\n" 2 3 5
        Print an arithmetic statement.

    printf "%-20s %5d\n" "Item" 42
        Left-align a string, right-align a number.

    printf "%08.2f\n" 3.14159
        Zero-padded float with 2 decimal places: 00003.14

    printf "%x\n" 255
        Print 255 in hexadecimal: ff

    printf "%s\n" apple banana cherry
        Print each argument on its own line (FORMAT reused).

    printf "%b" "line1\nline2\n"
        Interpret escapes in a string argument.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success.
    1   Error occurred.
